{"pos":"noun","gloss":"verbal noun of قَدَّ (qadda) (form I)","tags":["form-of","noun-from-verb"]},{"pos":"noun","gloss":"cutting, cutting off"},{"pos":"noun","gloss":"size, stature, figure"},{"pos":"noun","gloss":"length"},{"pos":"noun","gloss":"definite measure or quantity"},{"pos":"noun","gloss":"equal of a person or thing"},{"pos":"noun","gloss":"lambskin"},{"pos":"noun","gloss":"strip, shred"},{"pos":"noun","gloss":"split"},{"pos":"noun","gloss":"caesura"},{"pos":"particle","gloss":"Indicates nearness in time or recentness, recently, just now","tags":["past"],"examples":[{"text":"قَدْ وَصَلَ","english":"he has arrived; he had arrived"},{"text":"كَانَ (قَدْ) وَصَلَ","english":"he had arrived"}]},{"pos":"particle","gloss":"Indicates nonveridicality, might, could, may","examples":[{"text":"قَدْ يَكُونُ كَذٰلِكَ","english":"It may be so."},{"text":"إِنْ سَأَلْتَهُ ٱلْمَالَ فَقَدْ يُعْطِيكَ.","english":"If you ask him for money, he may give you."}]},{"pos":"particle","gloss":"Expresses emphasis","tags":["obsolete"],"examples":[{"text":"قَدْ يَعْلَمُ اللَّهُ الْمُعَوِّقِينَ مِنْكُمْ وَٱلْقَائِلِينَ لِإِخْوَانِهِمْ هَلُمَّ إِلَيْنَا وَلَا يَأْتُونَ الْبَأْسَ إِلَّا قَلِيلًا","english":"God does know the hinderers among you and the ones telling their brethren, \"Over here!\" These fight in wars only rarely."}]},{"pos":"noun","gloss":"cod (the fish)"}]},"etymology":{"source":"wiktextract","text":"Inherited from Proto-Semitic, probably of onomatopoeic origin. See قَتَّ (qatta).\nCognate to Hebrew קָדַד (qāḏaḏ), Aramaic קָדַד (qāḏaḏ, “to cut out”), Classical Syriac ܩܰܕ (qadd, “to tear or cut away”), Ge'ez ቀደ (ḳäddä, “to cut open, to tear apart”), Mehri ḳdd (“to shave off, to cut off, to scalp”).\n\nFrom the root ق د د (q d d) in the sense of being a thing separated or cut apart, a thing distinct with its own measure and shape, a defined piece; extended semantically to a secure definite thing, a certainty, hence the past tense implying a thing has already been set or definitive.\nThe non-past tense stems from the idea of something intended, likely expected, planned to be, measured to occur, or cut out to happen.\n\nBorrowed from English cod, as the range of the fish does not overlap with typical Arabic-speaking areas; compare Hebrew קוד (kod, “cod”). Compare also its other names مُورَة (mūra, “cod”) borrowed from French morue, and غادُس (ḡādus, “cod”) borrowed from Latin gadus (“generic term for fish; cod”). But the word قُدّ as a type of fish appears in two early Arabic-Arabic dictionaries, the Qamus of al-Fīrūzābādī (1329–1414) and the 'Ubaab of al-Saghānī (1181-1252), suggesting that a borrowing from English is most improbable. Perhaps from Greek γάδος?"},"ipa":["/qad.da/","/qadd/","/qad/","/qudd/"]}